XScreensaver is an utility for unix systems to privide a lock screen and a screensaver to manage better the power of your computer. Its an ancient software but can still be used. Such lightweight linux distribuitions use it in replacement of gnome-screensaver like: Crunchbang Linux - based on Debian and Arch Linux(Most users of Arch use WindowManagers like: Fluxbox, Openbox, i3wm, etc...)

# Installation
XScreensaver is probably on your distro repositories. I use Debian and it is there.
{% highlight bash %}
$ sudo apt-get install xscreensaver
{% endhighlight %}

# Setting up
After install you can change several things like: What screensaver to display, the timeout, if its going to be powersave... To enter on panel just type on your terminal:
{% highlight bash %}
$ xscreensaver-command --prefs
{% endhighlight %}
<br />
![xscreensaver advanced tab](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
<br />
![xscreensaver selecting a screensaver](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
<br />
By default the lock screen looks pretty ugly with an ancient computer in fire. This logo was designed by Angela Goodman.<br />
![Default Lock screen](data:image/png;base64,)
<br />

# Custumization

To custumize xscreensaver colors you can edit the file: ~/.Xresources in your user folder with a few parameters. You can google it, but I'm focused in show you how to change the computer on fire ugly logo.

# Getting sources packages
Now we are going to re-compile xscreensaver and change the logos. To get the sources put the source repositorie in your /etc/apt/sources.list and update your apt.<br />
To download the source code type the following commands:
{% highlight bash %}
$ sudo apt-get install dpkg-dev
$ sudo apt-get source xscreensaver
{% endhighlight %} 
<br />
# Switching the Logo
With your source downloaded navigate to folder /xscreensaver-5.15/utils/images/ <br />
This is the folder where its stored the logos. To change the logo you must replace with another file with the some restrictions (name and extension) you can use GIMP to regenerate your files. I used :)
<br />
![ My custom logo files](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

# Setting dependencies to compile
Before compile your new xscreensaver with a new logo, you must solve some dependencies (Remember, its based on Debian 7.0).
{% highlight bash %}
$ sudo apt-get install libgd2-xpm libgd2-xpm-dev libgdk-pixbuf2.0-0 libgdk-pixbuf2.0-dev 
libglade2-0 libglade2-dev libjpeg8-dev libxpm4 libxpm-dev libxt-dev
{% endhighlight %}
<br />
# Compiling with new logo
Remember to remove the previous apt-get package from your computer before compile by your own. If you want to change the logo in a near future keep safe the source code, because you are going to need to recompile everytime you change!
{% highlight bash %}
$ sudo apt-get remove xscreensaver
$ sudo ./configure
$ sudo make
$ sudo make install
{% endhighlight %}
<br />
Wait till compile and its done! Now you can run xscreensaver-command --prefs and check the new logo (Remember to restart your X after compile to make effect!). My new logo now look like this:<br />

![My xscreensaver recompiled](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
